column18:
I was actually hooked when I learned that data is the new oil. From hereon I am sinking deeper and was able to learn relevant and relatable information on this course.

What probably changed within me is my view on Data,  that Data's on their raw form is not very useful. It needs to be mined and extracted in such a way that it becomes useful for the right people. Hence I changed my way of reporting to my Supervisor.  Showing him what I think is the right visualization/presentation (my own choice). Trend shows the team performance for the past months. I was able to present it in such way that he began to think why on this particular month the teams performance is week. I backed him up because we are aware of the issue. Now what I am pushing forward is what can we do to optimize the teams performance. 

Insights when backed up by a data with value becomes so impactful that you have no way to ignore it. And it does not stop from there as I was forced to evaluate if I need to calibrate my way of thinking almost every time I finish my reports and assessment. It was both rewarding and challenging. I am very happy that I was able to continue my first course. I am truly grateful of this chance to upskill. Thank you Project SPARTA Team.

column18:
I was hooked when I learned that Data is the new oil. From here on, I was able to look at the data in a different perspective. That DATA in its raw form is not at all useful but when mined and integrated becomes useful for the right people.

I became immersed in making my report in such way that the I need to choose the right visualization method (my own choice) to present the trend of accomplishment of the teams handling the projects which I monitor. I was able to present my first report to my supervisor and showed him performance of the team which resulted in him thinking why the team has a weak performance on this particular month to which I agree as we both know the issue. 

We cannot ignore the impact of the insight derived from an integrated data and not act upon it.

It also pose as challenge as you cannot stop after the report is done, it is a cycle of improving a process and think of a way to optimize it. 

Thank you Project SPARTA Team.

column19:
I think that video learning is generally not very effective, especially when learning a highly technical subject like data analytics. When people watch course videos, the engagement is very passive and they may not absorb all of the concepts being told.

Thus, I think that the course would have been better if it were entirely in text paragraphs. People can better remember what they read, and it would also allow them to be slow and careful with the material. Though a transcript is provided, it is formatted line-by-line instead of by paragraphs or bullet points, so it becomes less effective for reading purposes.

I also think that other than the set of 10 questions at the end of the week, there should also be 1 multiple choice question at the bottom of each course page so that students can test their knowledge immediately after each part of the lesson.

column19:
The subject-matter expert or writers for this course must write the learning materials as if their target audience is second-year high school students or below. For example, I've seen too many adverbs and jargon. We must show, not tell. As an educator, we must not get caught up by what we know if others can't understand abstract concepts. So, it's good to use concrete words when we explain. 

Also, when we teach, it must be narrative. That way, learners hook up with what we're trying to point out. Analytics people are good storytellers. We will be better with storytelling in time.

As someone who is just getting started with the course, I think that the pacing and the selection of topics involved in this first course are very useful in helping me understand Data Analytics better. What I liked the most about the course is that it provides several ways for me to learn. Not just my watching the videos, but also because of the transcripts as I am able to review some of the concepts. 

In terms of the topics, I liked that the course included a real-life example on how Data Analytics may impact an organization. I think in this part of the course, when the lecturer was explaining what the roles of Data Analytics are through a case, I was able to visualize the application better and I was able to learn the importance of Data Analytics in every organization.

column19:
Remove the peer assessment essay. 

While a real life scenario questions are hard to formulate but are needed in this course but it shouldn't delay the learning of the students (I mean we could only contact after a week). 

Remember that most of the students here are professional and allotting their rest time to complete this. If in case, the student just took a leave to study the modules, there's a hard stop that would happen for the peer reviews. 

I think instead of having an essay, a case study is more appropriate with selection or a fill in the blanks with specific answer rather than wait for someone to pick up their answer. 

This is also how online corporate trainings go. It's "in your own pace" for a reason. Having a road block can be detrimental.

column19: The instructor could narrate more of his personal experiences with regard to the subject matter and even at various portions of the lecture. In this way, the direct application to real-life situations allows the students to appreciate the lessons better and relate the ideas to the opportunities and challenges that they would face in the future. One course where I found the instructor constantly relating the lessons to his wealth of professional experience is in Udemy entitled How to Get a Job in IT (https://www.udemy.com/course/how-to-get-a-job-in-it/). The instructor, Bryan Cairns, even manages to provide humorous anecdotes which make for a fun learning experience. column19:
Increase your brains capacity to learn
The first eight tips are really about how to get the best result from your brains current "learning capacity. By learning capacity I mean the  physical structure of your brain, including all the neural networks that determine how well you can think (your memory, attention, speed of processing and ability to sequence ideas). Imagine if you could increase your brains ability to do those things better. Thanks to recent neuroscience research and the conversion of that into a range of brain training programs we all now have the ability to improve our learning capacity. Then when you use the learning tips 1  8, you will get an even better learning outcome.

column19: The delivery of content is one of the most difficult and crucial components of creating an online course. Since the core of any course is its content, how that knowledge is delivered to students has a significant impact on their success and happiness. Regardless of the platform you select to provide that content on, there are a number of best practices that can be employed to guarantee that your students are learning the material they need to succeed. The ideal approach to present content varies depending on the course, but there are a number of them. The best practices for delivering content online and face-to-face are similar in many ways.

column18: The content is very logical. I must admit that I learn a lot from this course. I would like to share you a story. Just recently, I went to an institution where their goal is to help kids from 1 yr old up to the age of 25. I was lucky enough to talk to a 2nd year college students, studying in TUP, majoring in Computer Science and Math. I found out that his interest lies on the field of Data Analytics. Pardon me, but I used whatever I learned from this course and discuss it to him. I started with the Data Value Chain, then discuss to him the Analytics job families. In all honesty, if I didn't sign up in this course, I might be giving him the wrong information on analytics. Bottom line, I was able to piqued his interest and I can honestly say that he learned something from me, all thanks to this course. So, if we're talking of "particularly rewarding"? This is a classic example of a "reward" made in heaven.
